Certainly! You can set the `src` and attributes of an `<iframe>` element using JavaScript. Here's an example of how you can do it:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>IFrame Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <iframe id="myIframe" width="600" height="400" frameborder="0"></iframe>

    <script>
        // Get a reference to the iframe element
        var iframe = document.getElementById("myIframe");

        // Set the src attribute
        iframe.src = "https://www.example.com";

        // Set other attributes (optional)
        iframe.allowfullscreen = true;
        iframe.allow = "camera; microphone"; // Example of setting multiple permissions

        // You can also set styles for the iframe
        iframe.style.border = "2px solid red";
        iframe.style.borderRadius = "10px";
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the JavaScript code retrieves the `<iframe>` element by its ID (`"myIframe"`), sets the `src` attribute to "https://www.example.com", and adds some optional attributes and styling to the iframe. Make sure to replace "https://www.example.com" with the actual URL you want to use for the iframe's content.

