Certainly! To add an event listener for messages in an HTML page, you can use the `window.addEventListener` method with the `"message"` event type. This is commonly used to communicate between different windows, frames, or iframes using the `postMessage` API. Here's an example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Message Event Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <iframe id="myIframe" src="iframe.html" width="600" height="400" frameborder="0"></iframe>

    <script>
        // Get a reference to the iframe element
        var iframe = document.getElementById("myIframe");

        // Add a message event listener
        window.addEventListener("message", function(event) {
            // Check the origin of the message for security purposes
            if (event.origin === "https://www.example.com") {
                // Handle the received message data
                console.log("Received message:", event.data);
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the main HTML page includes an `<iframe>` with the `src` attribute set to "iframe.html". The JavaScript code in the main page sets up a message event listener using the `window.addEventListener` method. When a message is sent from the iframe using the `postMessage` API, the listener will receive the message and handle it. The `event.origin` property is used to ensure that the message is coming from an expected source for security purposes.

Inside the iframe (`iframe.html` in this case), you can send a message to the parent window using the `postMessage` API like this:

```javascript
// Send a message to the parent window
window.parent.postMessage("Hello from the iframe!", "https://your-main-page-domain.com");
```

Make sure to replace `"https://your-main-page-domain.com"` with the actual domain of your main HTML page.

